# Environment variables for single-customer pilot deployment
# Copy this file to .env and configure for the customer. Never commit .env.

# Public hostname for this customer's pilot deployment.
# Example: customer-name-kb.yourdomain.com
PUBLIC_HOST=example.com

# Required access control for first pilots.
# Generate with:
# docker run --rm caddy:2-alpine caddy hash-password --plaintext 'yourpassword'
#
# If the generated hash contains dollar signs, wrap it in single quotes in .env
# so Docker Compose does not treat them as variable interpolation.
BASIC_AUTH_USER=admin
BASIC_AUTH_HASH='replace-with-caddy-hash'

# Default production-speed inference path for paid pilots.
# Use a customer-approved OpenAI-compatible endpoint when required.
OPENAI_API_KEY=sk-replace-me

# Azure OpenAI alternative:
# AZURE_OPENAI_ENDPOINT=https://YOUR_RESOURCE.openai.azure.com/
# AZURE_OPENAI_API_KEY=...

# Notes:
# - Use one VPS and one .env per customer for first pilots.
# - Keep customer-specific data in separate folders.
# - Configure DNS to point PUBLIC_HOST to the VPS IP before deployment.
# - Caddy will automatically obtain Let's Encrypt HTTPS certificates.
# - Do not use laptop Ollama for paid-pilot production speed.
# - Use pilot-private-gpu only when hosted inference is forbidden and the GPU host passes the latency target.

# Deployment checklist:
# 1. Set PUBLIC_HOST to the customer's domain.
# 2. Configure DNS A/AAAA records.
# 3. Generate and set BASIC_AUTH_HASH.
# 4. Set OPENAI_API_KEY or the customer-approved hosted endpoint credentials.
# 5. Copy this file to .env.
# 6. Run: docker compose -f docker-compose.yml -f docker-compose.pilot.yml up -d
# 7. Verify HTTPS works at https://${PUBLIC_HOST}.
# 8. Test basic auth login before inviting users.
# 9. Configure Kotaemon with config/inference/pilot-hosted.example.yml.
# 10. Upload only approved customer docs.
